bject.getInstance is nonexistent — I wonder about alternatives if a class has a reflective getInstance method and whether metadata is accessible through JUnit. Could I utilize the test class's public method? However, if JUnit registers methods, it typically does so for no-arg tests, not static ones. I’m wondering if all methods in the test class can register through JUnit's native reflection. Maybe the getInstance(Object) method could work if it's in the same test class?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating JUnit reflections**\\n\\nI'm considering how JUnit invokes test methods reflectively and whether that metadata includes static methods like getInstance(Object). It seems JUnit might scan class metadata to include declared methods. I’m thinking about using public static getInstance in the test class, perhaps helping with ItsUtils.fillList. However, fillList casts the return to T, and I'm unsure if type needs to extend or match something specific. The method seems intended for certain ASN1 types, but the helper isn’t part of a specific library package. It’s a bit complex!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying test file rules**\\n\\nI’m trying to figure out the rules for testing a dynamic-access class. It looks like I need a dedicated Java test file that’s public and doesn’t include a dollar sign in the filename. Nested classes seem to be permitted, but should I avoid nested helpers? I can't create a package-private helper class, so I should stick to a public top-level helper or use a public static method in the test class instead. This way, I can use ItsUtilsAnonymous1Test.class as needed, since that class is public and straightforward, enabling me to build instances easily.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining reflection in test classes**\\n\\nI'm considering how native reflection in test classes might focus only on methods. It seems likely that all declared methods could be included, but for something like getMethod, it looks like I need the metadata for the public method getInstance(Object). The class metadata might be comprehensive. I wonder if this qualifies as \\\"normal public API.\\\" Since ItsUtils.fillList is a public generic method that uses getInstance, would that provide the necessary coverage, or does it focus more on library metadata rather than user-defined helpers? It’s a bit tricky!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_CJcn2cYxWds3LkvPEMLAm5ZY|fc_046dc510cb1c89d0016a25ce480be88195a8799302486e6fff", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcutil-jdk15to18/1.77/test-results-native/test/TEST-junit-jupiter.xml", "offset": 121, "limit": 100}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 684, "output": 1159, "cacheRead": 27136, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 28979, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780862508815, "responseId": "resp_046dc510cb1c89d0016a25ce2d6c4c8195983d6b999692e3f6"}}
