[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring JUnit test registration**\n\nI’m trying to figure out how Native JUnit registers test class methods. It looks like it invokes test methods reflectively, possibly registering only certain methods unless scanning reveals more. JUnit usually discovers methods and filters annotations at runtime, but native test frameworks might rely on compile-time test lists. \n\nIf a method like `getInstance` isn’t being picked up, it might help to annotate it correctly. Can't use `@Test` with invalid parameters, but maybe `@TestFactory` could work? I wonder if using `@ParameterizedTest` could also be a solution.\n\n**Clarifying JUnit method requirements**\n\nI'm trying to figure out the requirements for a static method in ItsUtils. It looks like JUnit's `@ParameterizedTest` isn't typically static, and I’m not sure if test methods can return non-void. JUnit 5 might allow static test methods, as long as they aren't private. \n\nI think the standard `@Test` method needs to be public and void, but I’m not operating on firm ground here. Also, I wonder about using `@RegisterForReflection` from GraalVM Native Image. Is that dependency available?\n\n**Navigating Metadata Confusion**\n\nI'm seeing a conflict between what the user has requested regarding metadata and what the developer has stated. The user mentioned modifying metadata, but the developer insists we shouldn't. It seems like if we don’t modify it, we can't cover everything in native runs. I wonder if Forge is managing metadata generation when tests run under the JVM. Yet, it's also mentioned that dynamic coverage requires committed metadata. The user appears to be focused only on tests.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_046dc510cb1c89d0016a25ceaaf2bc8195a530314cae97bd5b\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJc7Gl_FTWlZAjmC1LA9KzyxSJ4-uDIHvs7SYgUQiQGZx5ZWHtaMF0B6B71l9JPL88WCjqC